  "category_subtitle": "Counting days in Japanese",
  "category_detail": "<b>Counting Days in Japanese (日 / にち / nichi)</b><br><br>In Japanese, days are counted using the counter <b>日</b>. However, the first ten days have many <b>special and irregular readings</b> that must be memorized.<br><br><b>Irregular Days</b><br>Unlike most counters, the first ten days do not follow the normal number + にち pattern.<br><br><span class=\"example\">1日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ついたち / tsuitachi)</span><br><span class=\"example\">2日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ふつか / futsuka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">3日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(みっか / mikka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">4日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(よっか / yokka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">5日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(いつか / itsuka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">6日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(むいか / muika)</span><br><span class=\"example\">7日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(なのか / nanoka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">8日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ようか / youka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">9日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ここのか / kokonoka)</span><br><span class=\"example\">10日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(とおか / tooka)</span><br><br><b>After 10</b><br>From day 11 onward, Japanese usually follows a regular pattern using <b>〜日 (にち / nichi)</b>.<br><br><span class=\"example\">11日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(じゅういちにち / juuichi nichi)</span><br><span class=\"example\">20日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(はつか / hatsuka)</span><br><br><b>Important Exception</b><br><span class=\"example\">20日</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(はつか / hatsuka)</span><br>This is another special reading and does not follow the normal pattern.",

